We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the following:

Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;

Property Officer to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;  


Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the Property Officer;


Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set foth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect a more reliable balances of PPE accounts.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Direct the Revenue Collectors to ensure that collections made for the current day are strictly remitted to the Municipal Treasurer on a daily basis and require them to accomplish the RCDs at the close of each business day;
Require the Liquidating Officer to thoroughly verify all collections turned over to her and accomplish the RCD;
The Municipal Treasurer to perform verification of RCD such as checking the statement of accountable forms, conducting a physical count of accountable forms and reconciling them with records, counting the cash received and ensuring it matches the reported collections and sign the certification and receipt portion of all RCD copies; and
Likewise, the Treasurer to ensure that deposits are made with the authorized government depository bank daily or not later than the next banking day.
These measures will ensure timely remittance and compliance with established rules and regulations, thereby strengthening the Municipality's internal control system.

To ensure that inventories are safeguarded against the risk of misapplication or misuse, we have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to implement the following:
Record inventory using the prescribed perpetual method of accounting and strictly adhere to the pro-forma accounting entries on all purchased supplies and materials;
Maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards for each type of supplies and materials;
Conduct regular reconciliation of the ledger and the stock cards to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for; and
Ensure the reliability and accuracy of the accounts presented in the financial statements.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:
Re-organize the Inventory Committee in a memorandum or  Executive Order responsible for the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;  The committee may have same composition with ispection committee of the LGU but with technical knowhow in the conduct of physical count, property ledger cards and property cartds.
Designate a Property Officer to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the Property Officer;
Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect reliable balances of PPE accounts.
Furthermore, we have recommended that all issued property and equipment with a unit cost below the capitalization threshold of P50,000.00, that are still included in the PPE accounts, be appropriately derecognized from the PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2022-004, dated May 31, 2022, and COA Circular No. 2024-006, dated March 14, 2024.

We have recommended the Mayor to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct analysis and review the cause of discrepancy by tracing and locating the documents affecting the reciprocal accounts;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts through the preparation of a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) duly supported with documents, explanations, and/or computations in order to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;
Maintain subsidiary ledger and conduct regular reconciliation of the accounts to ensure that the balances of reciprocal accounts are the same at all times.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, and the concerned municipal employee to:
Observe the timely remittance of tax dues/withheld from employees/suppliers, premium contributions of both employer and employee, as well as the loan repayments to the concerned Offices, as the case may be, as prescribed by BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid possible penalties;
Remit all taxes withheld, premium contributions, and loan repayment intact on or before the deadline as provided in the rules and regulations set by the BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid penalties, surcharges, and interests from delayed remittances;
Reconcile the Due to BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth accounts with the actual amounts withheld based on the filed tax returns, statement of account, and loan amortization schedule from respective agencies, to identify the under- and over-remittances incurred from prior years until the current year; and
Encourage all employees to download and use GSIS, PAGIBIG and Philhealth apps in mobile devices to monitor personal contributions, claims, and loan payments.

For the Management to have an assurance that inventories are safeguarded against risk of misapplication or misuse, we recommended the Municipal Mayor to direct the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer the following:

To record inventory using the prescribed perpetual method of accounting and strictly adhere with the pro-forma accounting entries on all purchased supplies and materials;



To maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards for each type of supplies and materials;



To conduct regular reconciliation of the ledger and the stock cards to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for; and

To ensure the reliability and accuracy of the accounts presented in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer the following:

To designate liquidating officer to assist him in performing the procedures for the receipt and verification of collections remitted by the collectors;

To regularly update the cashbooks to reflect the exact amount of collections and deposits;

To ensure that all collections shall be deposited to the particular fund or funds to which the monies properly belong; and

The erring accountable officer/s shall submit written explanation on the matter. If no satisfactory explanation was provided, the overage shall be forfeited in favor of the Municipal Government.

